<div id="review_1433774230" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1433774230" />
    <a title="Suha" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/33599214-suha"><img alt="Suha" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1407013913p2/33599214.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1433774230?book_show_action=true">Nov 04, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Suha" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Suha" href="/user/show/33599214-suha">Suha</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1433774230" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1200361835830405486">I am wondering if I should consider this book a self-help book with a philosophical aspect in which the author attempts to address life’s difficulties through a trip with the well-known philosophers.<br/> For instance, he starts with Socrates and the consolation for unpopularity: the author sheds the light on the fact that we tend to associate what is popular with what is right. “We may be silenced by impressive figures who tell us forcefully that money is essential to virtue”. Moreover, he quotes So</span>
  <span id="freeText1200361835830405486" style="display:none">I am wondering if I should consider this book a self-help book with a philosophical aspect in which the author attempts to address life’s difficulties through a trip with the well-known philosophers.<br /> For instance, he starts with Socrates and the consolation for unpopularity: the author sheds the light on the fact that we tend to associate what is popular with what is right. “We may be silenced by impressive figures who tell us forcefully that money is essential to virtue”. Moreover, he quotes Socrates: “Are you not ashamed that you give your attention to acquiring as much money as possible, and similarly with reputation and honor, and give no attention or thought to truth and understanding and the perfection of your soul”. As a result, we should be judged by our logic of justice and injustice not as to conformity with the majority.<br />De Botton consoles us with not having enough money through the philosophy of Epicurus and how lived his life first seeking pleasures of food and sex claiming that he had to vomit twice a day because he ate so much. Throughout his quest of happiness, he found the following building blocks: Friendship, freedom, and thought as the necessary musts for happiness which in fact are not related to money. <br />As for frustration, the consolation comes from Seneca, and he quotes “we are mistaken if we believe any part of the world is exempt and safe”; so bad things will surely occur, but they won’t be as bad as we fear and our only way to survive the frustration is to accept that it is only a normal aspect of life. <br />Montaigne was the philosopher chosen for the consolation of inadequacy; Montaigne criticized the unhappy scholars who were always looking for more whereas he found the goats to be happiest saying the following “she had never read the Tusculan Disputations nor Cicero’s On the Laws, and yet she seemed content nibbling at stray pieces of lettuce…” so he questioned whether the mind gave us anything to be grateful for as it carried pain, worries, jealousy, greed and untamable appetites. The topics of sexual inadequacy, cultural inadequacy and intellectual inadequacy were addressed with simplicity and acceptance of what life offered us; striving for wisdom but not far from folly is achievement enough.<br />The broken heart was consoled by Schopenhauer by addressing the matter of love; where love’s ultimate aim is not intellectual entertainment but the procreation of children. It is solely a key to continuation of the species. As he was broken hearted many times, he claims the answers to why him or why her lies in the answer of producing healthy children and intelligent offspring; a manifestation of the will to life. <br />The last chapter tackles difficulties, and Nietzsche, throughout his life’s journey in writing discovered that the most fulfilling human projects are inseparable from a degree of torment and that the sources of our greatest joys are close to those of our greatest pains. Nietzsche wrote most of his work while being in contact in nature; in a stage of his life, he got interested in gardening and he discovered that in the roots of a plant lie anger, pity, curiosity and vanity, whereas it blossoms into art, beauty and love. In our hearts, we long for belongings, success, fame and power; but those who do not have it, claim that as per Christianity, they are indifferent to what they secretly long for; as people must face difficulties to achieve and be joyous of what they have. <br />Critique: in my opinion, this book is great for those who are not aware of the philosophies/philosophers; it is a sort of a recap; moreover, it gives great insight of consolations on the stated doors of unhappiness based on strong philosophical foundations which in my opinion is similar to what is prevalent in our days through the recent self-help books. There are some figures/ illustrations in this book, showing sometimes paintings, the philosophers themselves, some photos and a visual aid of what is stated. Easy tone, straightforward, and what I also liked is that it takes you back to a small biography of the philosophers themselves. I do recommend <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="1200361835830405486" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


