<div id="review_1378524026" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1378524026" />
    <a title="Mehwish Mughal" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/24694373-mehwish-mughal"><img alt="Mehwish Mughal" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1611015327p2/24694373.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1378524026?book_show_action=true">Aug 30, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mehwish Mughal" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mehwish Mughal" href="/user/show/24694373-mehwish-mughal">Mehwish Mughal</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780141038377" href="/book/show/5272805-the-consolations-of-philosophy">review of another edition</a>


          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Mehwish by: </span>
      <a href="/user/show/4777656-mjaballah">Mjaballah</a>
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/24694373-mehwish-mughal?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/24694373-mehwish-mughal?shelf=my-own-my-precious">my-own-my-precious</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/24694373-mehwish-mughal?shelf=recommendations">recommendations</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1378524026" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5879089138109353632"><i> The Background story </i><br/><br/>About 2 years ago, I was having a conversation with a friend about the whys and hows of life. He suggested that I read <b> The Consolations of Philosophy </b>.<br/>Back then I was only interested in hard sciences and never even thought in my wildest dreams that I would be reading philosophy and 2 years later switch my education from Science to Arts. <br/><br/>So, when I read the book I was in complete fascination with the philosophers and their philosophies. I went further and read extensively o</span>
  <span id="freeText5879089138109353632" style="display:none"><i> The Background story </i><br /><br />About 2 years ago, I was having a conversation with a friend about the whys and hows of life. He suggested that I read <b> The Consolations of Philosophy </b>.<br />Back then I was only interested in hard sciences and never even thought in my wildest dreams that I would be reading philosophy and 2 years later switch my education from Science to Arts. <br /><br />So, when I read the book I was in complete fascination with the philosophers and their philosophies. I went further and read extensively on Socrates, Epicurus and Nietzsche. Socrates became my hero. As days rolled into months, and months into years, more books were read and this one became a part of my subconscious helping me make the tough decisions in life, cementing my personality and ideologies without ever surfacing in my conscious mind. I constantly suggested this book to my reader friends who stay clear of the path of philosophy regarding it as something that messes with your brain. Now, I do not know whether that claim is real or not because of course I have no idea whether my brain is deluded or functional. <br /><br />2 years later, my sister finished the book (after a lot of coaxing and pressure) and returned it back. I had a very curious feeling about this book which apparently turned my life around 180 degrees and I decided to read again to see whether I feel the same way that I felt back then or have I grown out of it. And oh yes! All those memories came floating back.<br /><br /><i> The actual review </i><br /><br />The book is divided into six sections. <br />1- On unpopularity (Socrates)<br />2- Not having enough money (Epicurus)<br />3- Frustration (Seneca)<br />4- Inadequacy (Montaigne)<br />5- A broken heart (Schopenhauer)<br />6- Difficulties (Nietzsche)<br /><br />The writing style is accessible. The philosophers are simplified but then again that was the very reason I could get through the book without feeling overwhelmed. The philosophies are plucked from the greatest books and molded into a form that is relevant to the reader. <br /><br />As I read through it again I used a different set of eyes, I was not so much influenced by the philosophies (as I had been earlier) but by the philosophers and their individuality, their place and time in history, their influences and their thoughts. It was as if I could see right through. I felt much closer and nostalgic. <br /> <br />I critically analysed my life through this book after finishing every part and proudly came to a conclusion that I have taken a lot of things on board since the last time I read it. <br /><br />Will I read it again? Yes, if life permits, I will, in another 5 years.<br /><br /><br />I recommend it to all!<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="5879089138109353632" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


