<div id="review_348752552" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/348752552" />
    <a title="Liz" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9857088-liz"><img alt="Liz" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1361160881p2/9857088.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/348752552?book_show_action=true">Jun 14, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Liz" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Liz" href="/user/show/9857088-liz">Liz</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780141038377" href="/book/show/5272805-the-consolations-of-philosophy">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9857088-liz?shelf=have-book">have-book</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9857088-liz?shelf=did-not-finish">did-not-finish</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer348752552" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8618702109176789642">Book started off strong. I was very interested in the sections about Socrates, Epicurus &amp; Seneca. The philosophies of these guys are thousands of years old but still so relevant and applicable to life today. I was throughly enjoying how the author was telling you a little bit about the life and times of these guys and how their philosophies can give people of today consolations for their problems. Then we moved into wealthy whiny man&apos;s territory. Seriously I skimmed the whole second part of this</span>
  <span id="freeText8618702109176789642" style="display:none">Book started off strong. I was very interested in the sections about Socrates, Epicurus &amp; Seneca. The philosophies of these guys are thousands of years old but still so relevant and applicable to life today. I was throughly enjoying how the author was telling you a little bit about the life and times of these guys and how their philosophies can give people of today consolations for their problems. Then we moved into wealthy whiny man's territory. Seriously I skimmed the whole second part of this book. The last three guys; Montaigne, Schopenhauer &amp; Nietzsche, were so freaking annoying, 'oh poor me, I have so much money, but can't get it up and fresh, nubile girls half my age won't marry me' Please....old guys are just gross....deal with it! <br /><br />But seriously, maybe Botton didn't do their philosophies justice, but I don't see how a group of guys writing about their lives and thoughts that are mainly applicable to their specific lives is philosophy?? I have a niggling feeling that Botton dumb down the philosophies of these guys in order to sell a self help book using other people's ideas because I have touched on the last three guys work in my tertiary studies and they seemed deeper and less fucking whiny. Maybe Botton is the whiny inadequate bitch and that is how he interpreted their work or how he felt it was applicable to his life. I think I will do further inquiry into Mont, Scho and Nietz.....I mean how can a guy with such an awesome moustache be so damned whiny?!<br /><br />I recommend the first half of this book for everyone who wants to know a little bit of surface level philosophy, and the second half to nerdy, inadequate whiny men with small flaccid pensises that could never get a date and whose mother was too over-bearing.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8618702109176789642" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


