  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/66483546" />
    <a title="Smiley " class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2580971-smiley"><img alt="Smiley " src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1525349534p2/2580971.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/66483546?book_show_action=true">Aug 06, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Smiley " class="user" itemprop="url" name="Smiley " href="/user/show/2580971-smiley">Smiley </a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780140276619" href="/book/show/23423.The_Consolations_of_Philosophy">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer66483546" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16217645332556160029">I&apos;m a bit surprised when I don&apos;t see anything written here as my review since I read it with my written comments in the book years ago. Indeed, I decided to buy this seemingly readable and understandable nonfiction in the name of philosophy during one of my visits to GSE/UQ in Brisbane, Australia. The unthinkable timeframe then was 1997-2003 in which I enjoyed doing my research as well as wondered sometime if I could make it for such a pinnacle degree there. It&apos;s sheer perplexity in which, again</span>
  <span id="freeText16217645332556160029" style="display:none">I'm a bit surprised when I don't see anything written here as my review since I read it with my written comments in the book years ago. Indeed, I decided to buy this seemingly readable and understandable nonfiction in the name of philosophy during one of my visits to GSE/UQ in Brisbane, Australia. The unthinkable timeframe then was 1997-2003 in which I enjoyed doing my research as well as wondered sometime if I could make it for such a pinnacle degree there. It's sheer perplexity in which, again, no one could provide any feasible solution except myself and another eternal factor, that is, time.<br />Therefore, I delightfully read this consoling book superbly written by one of the contemporary authors in this noble field of, say, practical philosophy for those interested in shaping his/her life with good advice, smart quips and apt sense of humor. Find one to read, dear GR friends, then I'd find what I had jotted down in there and would add here later for more interesting points to ponder and take action so that we can enjoy keeping going in this hectic world with undaunting heart.</span>
