<div id="review_2382071275" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2382071275" />
    <a title="ar" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/25611710-ar"><img alt="ar" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2382071275?book_show_action=true">May 27, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="ar" class="user" itemprop="url" name="ar" href="/user/show/25611710-ar">ar</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2382071275" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17143451437677814090">I could listen to de Botton explain that there is a Russia sized meteor hurtling toward our planet and leave the conversation feeling understood and comforted. Hearing him describe his understanding of some of the greatest Western philosophers and philosophies was really quite a treat. Anecdotes and insights abound in an exploration of both the greatest and consoling ideas, as well as the minds and bodies they came from. As always , de Botton is reasonable, convincing, almost spookily in touch w</span>
  <span id="freeText17143451437677814090" style="display:none">I could listen to de Botton explain that there is a Russia sized meteor hurtling toward our planet and leave the conversation feeling understood and comforted. Hearing him describe his understanding of some of the greatest Western philosophers and philosophies was really quite a treat. Anecdotes and insights abound in an exploration of both the greatest and consoling ideas, as well as the minds and bodies they came from. As always , de Botton is reasonable, convincing, almost spookily in touch with the human condition. In the spirit of Montaigne's assertion that books are of value to the extent that they are practically helpful, I particularly enjoyed his exploration of heartbreak from the perspective of the will to life. Bleak yet consoling. <br /><br />Side note: I recently reached out to de Botton to thank him for his work, and he responded authentically and promptly. He's that kind of guy.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17143451437677814090" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


